00:00:23.290 --> 00:00:31.820
in the class who sent codes
to find these wavefronts when

00:00:31.820 --> 00:00:39.230
a shock, a step function is
moving along with velocity c.

00:00:39.230 --> 00:00:45.410
I had roughly drawn what
these three methods produced,

00:00:45.410 --> 00:00:49.830
but it was much better to see
it in Mr. Sekora's movie that's

00:00:49.830 --> 00:00:53.150
on 18.086 site.

00:00:53.150 --> 00:01:02.340
And sure enough, behind the
moving front is an overshoot,

00:01:02.340 --> 00:01:06.860
that reminds us of the Gibbs
phenomenon, from Lax-Wendroff,

00:01:06.860 --> 00:01:11.220
and I think it's sort of
unavoidable if we have

00:01:11.220 --> 00:01:15.360
a negative -- because one
of the three coefficients

00:01:15.360 --> 00:01:18.290
at the previous time is
negative for Lax-Wendroff,

00:01:18.290 --> 00:01:21.170
that's how it gets its
second order accuracy,

00:01:21.170 --> 00:01:24.160
and we see that better
accuracy in a much steeper,

00:01:24.160 --> 00:01:26.580
much steeper profile.

00:01:26.580 --> 00:01:29.600
Then Lax-Friedrichs,
if you've noticed,

00:01:29.600 --> 00:01:35.830
has a sort of jagged profile.

00:01:35.830 --> 00:01:38.600
Maybe you've realized
why that would be.

00:01:38.600 --> 00:01:45.430
Somehow Lax-Friedrichs kind of
operates on a staggered grid.

00:01:45.430 --> 00:01:49.140
We'll see, actually with -- I've
drawn a staggered grid here,

00:01:49.140 --> 00:01:50.770
so I can say what I mean.

00:01:50.770 --> 00:01:54.350
Lax-Friedrichs
computes this value

00:01:54.350 --> 00:01:59.770
from the two earlier
values there and then

00:01:59.770 --> 00:02:01.900
at the next level
again and so forth,

00:02:01.900 --> 00:02:09.690
so that actually, Lax-Friedrichs
is using two staggered grids

00:02:09.690 --> 00:02:11.350
separately.

00:02:11.350 --> 00:02:16.460
I think -- normally,
with Lax-Friedrichs,

00:02:16.460 --> 00:02:19.440
we call that n plus 1 and
n plus 2 and n plus 3,

00:02:19.440 --> 00:02:23.350
but the picture is still right,
so I think that's probably

00:02:23.350 --> 00:02:30.440
responsible for what you
see, that there's two waves,

00:02:30.440 --> 00:02:36.360
two fronts, right, one delta
x away from each other.

00:02:36.360 --> 00:02:40.070
And finally, upwind
is also smeared out.

00:02:40.070 --> 00:02:46.680
I guess I was so pleased to
see these actually showing

00:02:46.680 --> 00:02:51.670
on the website and that makes
me think of more questions.

00:02:51.670 --> 00:02:54.670
Maybe you too.

00:02:54.670 --> 00:03:00.230
First of all, as
time goes forward,

00:03:00.230 --> 00:03:03.500
we see this bump
beginning to appear.

00:03:03.500 --> 00:03:06.970
So am I right in thinking that
it reaches a certain height

00:03:06.970 --> 00:03:08.790
and stays there?

00:03:08.790 --> 00:03:13.170
So I guess I'm thinking about
sort of further questions,

00:03:13.170 --> 00:03:15.820
because every time you do
a numerical experiment,

00:03:15.820 --> 00:03:19.150
good additional
question show up.

00:03:19.150 --> 00:03:23.990
So I'm wondering, as
this wavefront forms,

00:03:23.990 --> 00:03:28.750
this characteristic profile
for these three methods,

00:03:28.750 --> 00:03:31.900
first of all, does that
profile settle down

00:03:31.900 --> 00:03:34.610
to a steady profile?

00:03:34.610 --> 00:03:37.110
Ultimately it'd be great
to be able to predict

00:03:37.110 --> 00:03:40.330
what it would be.

00:03:40.330 --> 00:03:43.300
In particular, does that
bump reach a certain height?

00:03:43.300 --> 00:03:45.770
Because you can see it just
barely forming and then

00:03:45.770 --> 00:03:48.650
you see it growing
to a certain point.

00:03:48.650 --> 00:03:52.200
And then, when the movie
ends, fortunately it

00:03:52.200 --> 00:03:55.210
plots this picture and you
really see the profile,

00:03:55.210 --> 00:03:57.420
and you can actually
see, if you look closely,

00:03:57.420 --> 00:04:02.460
that it goes above 1
again and probably more.

00:04:05.630 --> 00:04:10.580
That would be, does it
approach a steady profile?

00:04:10.580 --> 00:04:14.530
Does that height settle down?

00:04:14.530 --> 00:04:18.170
It'd be fantastic to be
able to predict that height.

00:04:18.170 --> 00:04:20.540
For example, you always
want to know, how do things

00:04:20.540 --> 00:04:22.780
depend on the parameter?

00:04:22.780 --> 00:04:26.510
The one parameter we have
in this problem is r --

00:04:26.510 --> 00:04:28.240
c delta t over delta x.

00:04:28.240 --> 00:04:32.180
If I change r, I'm changing
all the coefficients.

00:04:32.180 --> 00:04:36.790
If I changed r to be
exactly 1, then the profile

00:04:36.790 --> 00:04:38.500
would be perfect, right?

00:04:38.500 --> 00:04:43.370
That's the golden
ratio, r equal 1.

00:04:43.370 --> 00:04:48.280
I would be computing that
value exactly from this value,

00:04:48.280 --> 00:04:51.400
at exactly the right slope,
on the characteristic,

00:04:51.400 --> 00:04:54.330
and perfection.

00:04:54.330 --> 00:04:57.600
Now as r goes away
from 1, I presume --

00:04:57.600 --> 00:04:58.980
it goes down below 1.

00:04:58.980 --> 00:05:02.620
Of course, if it goes
above 1, catastrophe.

00:05:02.620 --> 00:05:08.140
If it goes below 1, I presume
the bump begins to appear,

00:05:08.140 --> 00:05:09.890
goes higher.

00:05:09.890 --> 00:05:11.530
I don't know.

00:05:11.530 --> 00:05:16.130
Could you see how the
dependence on r appears?

00:05:16.130 --> 00:05:23.030
And then I can even suggest
one more thing, which is --

00:05:23.030 --> 00:05:31.910
let's put a fourth
guy onto this picture,

00:05:31.910 --> 00:05:33.850
which would be leapfrog.

00:05:33.850 --> 00:05:36.350
Leapfrog for
first-order equations,

00:05:36.350 --> 00:05:40.210
so let me just put down
below what that would be.

00:05:40.210 --> 00:05:44.110
So it would be on that
kind of a staggered grid.

00:05:44.110 --> 00:05:46.800
A new value at
time n plus 1 would

00:05:46.800 --> 00:05:51.650
come from these at time n,
really, and this one, at time n

00:05:51.650 --> 00:05:52.370
minus 1.

00:05:52.370 --> 00:05:55.900
So leapfrog -- you'd
think of it right away.

00:05:55.900 --> 00:06:04.070
I use a centered difference in
time, U_(j, n+1) minus U_(j,

00:06:04.070 --> 00:06:09.850
n-1) over 2 delta t equals c
times a centered difference

00:06:09.850 --> 00:06:20.510
in space, U_(j+1, n) minus
U_(j-1, n) over 2 delta x.

00:06:20.510 --> 00:06:24.680
So you see right
away, the 2's cancel.

00:06:24.680 --> 00:06:29.325
The delta x times c -- the
delta t times c over delta x is

00:06:29.325 --> 00:06:36.110
our old ratio r, so this is
easily written in terms of r

00:06:36.110 --> 00:06:37.300
again.

00:06:37.300 --> 00:06:44.140
It does have this
two time step issue

00:06:44.140 --> 00:06:47.030
and of course, we have
to think about stability.

00:06:47.030 --> 00:06:53.960
I'm writing down a fourth
candidate for the equation u_t

00:06:53.960 --> 00:06:59.990
equals c*u_x, of course, before
I come back to the second-order

00:06:59.990 --> 00:07:03.020
equations, or systems.

00:07:03.020 --> 00:07:05.220
I just wanted to put
in these comments,

00:07:05.220 --> 00:07:11.500
partly because I'm thinking
about projects that are --

00:07:11.500 --> 00:07:20.120
and I hope you are -- so
some people will have theses

00:07:20.120 --> 00:07:28.030
or problems from other courses
which involve solving PDEs

00:07:28.030 --> 00:07:36.050
and that'd be perfectly
natural to base some project

00:07:36.050 --> 00:07:42.720
on, but if you don't have
some specific application,

00:07:42.720 --> 00:07:47.660
then here are a whole lot
of interesting questions,

00:07:47.660 --> 00:07:49.790
to just go further with that.

00:07:49.790 --> 00:07:59.150
So the dependence
on r would be a --

00:07:59.150 --> 00:08:08.700
the profile dependence on
r, c delta t over delta x,

00:08:08.700 --> 00:08:09.650
would be a question.

00:08:14.710 --> 00:08:18.240
Let me just emphasize,
what's the goal?

00:08:18.240 --> 00:08:21.330
When I say that this
upwind one is smeared out,

00:08:21.330 --> 00:08:26.190
I mean that it doesn't satisfy
what you really hope for.

00:08:26.190 --> 00:08:31.860
You want to capture that
shock, that discontinuity --

00:08:31.860 --> 00:08:34.710
not perfectly, you
can't expect that --

00:08:34.710 --> 00:08:39.980
but you want to capture it,
maybe in, let's say, 2 delta x.

00:08:39.980 --> 00:08:43.510
A good method captures
the shock within 2 delta x

00:08:43.510 --> 00:08:50.960
and does it without much
undesirable oscillation,

00:08:50.960 --> 00:08:54.250
physical oscillation like that.

00:08:54.250 --> 00:08:58.870
So these are methods where
we're trading off a good shock

00:08:58.870 --> 00:09:03.400
capture versus a smeared one,
which is not satisfactory,

00:09:03.400 --> 00:09:07.650
really, in a lot
of applications.

00:09:07.650 --> 00:09:12.060
So capturing the
shock within 2 delta

00:09:12.060 --> 00:09:19.200
x, roughly, is highly
desirable, and you

00:09:19.200 --> 00:09:24.290
might have to go add a
artificial viscosity that we'll

00:09:24.290 --> 00:09:28.300
discuss to get there.

00:09:28.300 --> 00:09:33.120
So that's past things, but
still very much present,

00:09:33.120 --> 00:09:34.340
if I can say.

00:09:34.340 --> 00:09:38.720
Here I've introduced
a new leapfrog,

00:09:38.720 --> 00:09:42.450
a one-way equation
leapfrog, I'll

00:09:42.450 --> 00:09:50.230
call this, where
the last lecture was

00:09:50.230 --> 00:09:52.520
about two-way leapfrog.

00:09:52.520 --> 00:09:56.040
Leapfrog for u_tt
equals c squared

00:09:56.040 --> 00:09:58.510
u_xx, a two-way wave equation.

00:09:58.510 --> 00:10:04.480
I might just mention about
this one-way leapfrog,

00:10:04.480 --> 00:10:10.170
once you put in e to the
i*k*x as we always do,

00:10:10.170 --> 00:10:17.240
or e to the i*k*j delta
x in the discrete case --

00:10:17.240 --> 00:10:27.100
so you would put in an e
to the i*j delta x times k,

00:10:27.100 --> 00:10:33.560
and then find the G,
the growth factor in --

00:10:33.560 --> 00:10:39.040
that'll depend on k and will
tell us the time dependence.

00:10:39.040 --> 00:10:40.550
It'll be a G to the n-th.

00:10:43.330 --> 00:10:48.790
I think you'll find
that for this guy,

00:10:48.790 --> 00:10:53.440
the absolute value of G is
exactly 1 while it's stable.

00:10:53.440 --> 00:10:57.130
Of course, if the Courant
condition is violated,

00:10:57.130 --> 00:10:59.670
then there's no way
it could be stable

00:10:59.670 --> 00:11:04.010
and G's will grow,
be bigger than 1.

00:11:04.010 --> 00:11:10.040
But, I think in the stable
range, you will have --

00:11:10.040 --> 00:11:13.290
this G will have
absolute value exactly 1.

00:11:16.960 --> 00:11:18.620
So it'll be on the unit circle.

00:11:18.620 --> 00:11:23.390
You don't have
much leeway, right?

00:11:23.390 --> 00:11:28.920
We found upwind was,
like, well inside;

00:11:28.920 --> 00:11:32.840
Lax-Friedrichs was well
inside; Lax-Wendroff,

00:11:32.840 --> 00:11:38.240
because it had higher
accuracy for low frequencies,

00:11:38.240 --> 00:11:44.210
was closer; and I think
this guy is right on.

00:11:44.210 --> 00:11:48.170
So this is the
first-order methods.

00:11:48.170 --> 00:11:50.220
This would be Lax-Wendroff
and this would

00:11:50.220 --> 00:11:53.150
be this second-order method.

00:11:53.150 --> 00:11:56.710
So you're really
playing with fire there

00:11:56.710 --> 00:12:00.630
and maybe this is
not a favorite, just

00:12:00.630 --> 00:12:04.920
because it's too close to
the edge, in fact, right

00:12:04.920 --> 00:12:06.530
on the edge.

00:12:06.530 --> 00:12:10.960
So those are some
comments really generated

00:12:10.960 --> 00:12:17.890
by your numerical experiments
and I think that's the way this

00:12:17.890 --> 00:12:23.490
course should -- homeworks and
projects should develop out

00:12:23.490 --> 00:12:26.740
of numerical experiment.

00:12:26.740 --> 00:12:31.730
Now I'll come back to
complete my lecture

00:12:31.730 --> 00:12:34.110
on the second-order
wave equation.

00:12:37.260 --> 00:12:43.110
So we studied leapfrog for that.

00:12:43.110 --> 00:12:47.000
I won't repeat that, but
then with second-order wave

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:49.730
equation, we have
another option,

00:12:49.730 --> 00:12:56.080
which is to reduce a
second-order equation with two

00:12:56.080 --> 00:13:01.260
time derivatives to a system
of two equations that are

00:13:01.260 --> 00:13:05.570
first order in time and space.

00:13:05.570 --> 00:13:12.310
I've chosen to use the letters
H and E as a kind of hint

00:13:12.310 --> 00:13:17.350
that we're touching a really
big application, which

00:13:17.350 --> 00:13:20.430
is electromagnetism.

00:13:20.430 --> 00:13:26.370
So E for the electric field, H
for the magnetic field but here

00:13:26.370 --> 00:13:35.400
in 1-D -- so it allows me
just to mention that in 3-D,

00:13:35.400 --> 00:13:39.160
when E has three components,
H has three components,

00:13:39.160 --> 00:13:45.310
this is really the curl and
this is really minus the curl.

00:13:45.310 --> 00:13:56.920
And the notes will show
the beautiful Yee mesh,

00:13:56.920 --> 00:14:05.790
staggered mesh that copies
for finite difference methods,

00:14:05.790 --> 00:14:11.700
the properties of the
curl, our interpretation

00:14:11.700 --> 00:14:16.210
of and the properties of -- that
Maxwell discovered the physics

00:14:16.210 --> 00:14:23.099
of, you know, current, magnetic
fields going around a wire that

00:14:23.099 --> 00:14:24.890
along which one an
electric field is going.

00:14:28.200 --> 00:14:31.670
But let me stay here
with one dimension.

00:14:31.670 --> 00:14:37.180
So first of all, can we recover
the wave equation from that?

00:14:37.180 --> 00:14:41.070
Let's just see that we haven't
left behind the wave equation.

00:14:45.190 --> 00:14:48.810
So I just take the
second derivative --

00:14:48.810 --> 00:14:51.820
so the second derivative -- I
just want to recover the wave

00:14:51.820 --> 00:14:56.360
equation so that I haven't lost
it here -- so this will be,

00:14:56.360 --> 00:14:58.810
if I -- I'm taking the time
derivative of the first

00:14:58.810 --> 00:15:07.220
equation, so I get d
second h dt dx, right?

00:15:07.220 --> 00:15:13.730
But by the useful, extremely
useful fact that this is

00:15:13.730 --> 00:15:20.060
the same as taking the t
derivative first and the x

00:15:20.060 --> 00:15:24.860
derivative second, now I
have the x derivative of this

00:15:24.860 --> 00:15:32.240
equation, so this is c --
now I have the x derivative,

00:15:32.240 --> 00:15:35.310
or c times it, so now
I'm up to c squared,

00:15:35.310 --> 00:15:39.920
the x derivative of the
x derivative, right?

00:15:43.310 --> 00:15:49.246
So we eliminated H, got back
to one equation, second order,

00:15:49.246 --> 00:15:50.370
and it's the wave equation.

00:15:53.660 --> 00:15:58.560
I want to show the same thing
now for finite differences.

00:15:58.560 --> 00:16:05.060
It's just -- it's such a simple
and useful device and our point

00:16:05.060 --> 00:16:09.610
will be that it works for --
just as well for differences.

00:16:09.610 --> 00:16:14.980
That allows us to do
this staggered grid idea.

00:16:14.980 --> 00:16:21.480
So the staggered grid idea
is, I'll do E on this grid,

00:16:21.480 --> 00:16:26.170
at these grid points,
H at the half points,

00:16:26.170 --> 00:16:32.750
E again at the integer points,
H again at the half points.

00:16:32.750 --> 00:16:41.790
Now, so my difference
method, leapfrog,

00:16:41.790 --> 00:16:46.390
on this staggered
mesh, will copy --

00:16:46.390 --> 00:16:54.900
so the first equation will
give E at the new time from

00:16:54.900 --> 00:16:59.770
the difference in
H at this time.

00:16:59.770 --> 00:17:02.250
So, you see it.

00:17:02.250 --> 00:17:08.810
dE/dt is going to be replaced
by that time difference.

00:17:08.810 --> 00:17:14.180
dH/dx is going to be replaced
by this space difference,

00:17:14.180 --> 00:17:16.420
and that will determine
E at the new time.

00:17:16.420 --> 00:17:21.280
So I need time 0 and
time 1/2 to get started.

00:17:21.280 --> 00:17:23.610
Maybe I put those
down here, somewhere.

00:17:23.610 --> 00:17:26.330
I have to use the
initial condition,

00:17:26.330 --> 00:17:33.710
the initial velocity to
get started on E and H

00:17:33.710 --> 00:17:35.990
and then I go onwards.

00:17:35.990 --> 00:17:38.470
I've got to this
point and this point.

00:17:38.470 --> 00:17:43.230
Then this guy comes from this
one, this one and this one.

00:17:46.520 --> 00:17:52.410
Of course, that similarly
comes from the same equation

00:17:52.410 --> 00:17:55.810
shifted over.

00:17:55.810 --> 00:17:56.980
Now I know these.

00:17:56.980 --> 00:17:59.540
Now I'm ready for this one.

00:17:59.540 --> 00:18:03.150
Coming from -- what am
I approximating now?

00:18:03.150 --> 00:18:09.270
I'm on the staggered part
of the grid, the half steps.

00:18:09.270 --> 00:18:14.220
I'm approximating this on the
half steps, where H is defined.

00:18:14.220 --> 00:18:18.990
So that minus that is
the time difference.

00:18:18.990 --> 00:18:23.380
This minus this -- which,
I know these now --

00:18:23.380 --> 00:18:26.190
is the space difference
in this equation,

00:18:26.190 --> 00:18:30.060
and that's what allows me
to compute the new one.

00:18:30.060 --> 00:18:33.940
You see, it's a simple idea.

00:18:33.940 --> 00:18:41.710
It's close but
different from my scalar

00:18:41.710 --> 00:18:44.580
leapfrog, one-way leapfrog here.

00:18:44.580 --> 00:18:49.140
Here it was the same
U at all the points.

00:18:49.140 --> 00:18:56.400
Here it is E at the integer
time levels and H at the half

00:18:56.400 --> 00:18:59.700
integer time levels.

00:18:59.700 --> 00:19:03.630
It's natural to say --
I'm calling this leapfrog.

00:19:06.990 --> 00:19:12.180
Could I do this for the
difference equation?

00:19:12.180 --> 00:19:17.760
I just want to see that
if I eliminate H --

00:19:17.760 --> 00:19:19.750
you saw what happened there.

00:19:19.750 --> 00:19:24.640
By using the identity that the
second derivative in t and x

00:19:24.640 --> 00:19:28.640
is always the same as the
second derivative in x and t,

00:19:28.640 --> 00:19:32.730
I eliminated H and got an
equation that involved E only.

00:19:36.550 --> 00:19:44.030
What's going to be the
corresponding identity?

00:19:44.030 --> 00:19:47.630
Trivial, but just -- trivial
things are not bad things

00:19:47.630 --> 00:19:51.820
to notice -- for the
different method.

00:19:54.760 --> 00:19:58.570
This is what I wanted to
be sure of, for the H part.

00:19:58.570 --> 00:20:05.460
This H -- so the H were -- do
you mind if I draw yet another

00:20:05.460 --> 00:20:06.650
symbol?

00:20:06.650 --> 00:20:11.840
I want to use this
idea to eliminate H. So

00:20:11.840 --> 00:20:15.270
let me put two H's there.

00:20:15.270 --> 00:20:16.700
Is that right?

